First, it is very unlikely ET knows about us. The universe is vast and apparently the chances of two intelligences occupying the same corner of it at the same time are extremely slim. Of course this is based on our current best estimates – which is all we really have to go on.<br>
<br>
I am not going to debate current knowledge. We do the best we can, and we know much is incomplete. Science is self-correcting, not dogmatic; at least it is suppose to be. When science becomes entangled in politics and/or causes it can be misused. Anything can be misused.<br>
<br>
The future will attend to itself, but only if we attend to the present. We don’t have warp drive, but if such a thing is possible we will find it; but only if we get out there and look. Waiting and hoping for magic is foolish; going out and making it isn’t.<br>
<br>
We need off this rock yesterday. We need space stations, lunar villages, and men on Mars. Only then will we start to make progress toward the stars. It will be a long, hard road filled with glory and failure; but it beats the hell out of staying put and slowly dying. We are explorers, nomads, and wonderers. Expand or die. <br>
<br>
As for Bush and Blare, well I didn’t vote for either. But Bush beats the hell out of Gore, and Blare isn’t so bad for a socialists. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/alien.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
